<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920303-0117</DOCNO><DOCID>920303-0117.</DOCID><HL>   Duracell to Eliminate Mercury</HL><DATE>03/03/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><CO>   DUR</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)NON-DURABLE HOUSEWARE PRODUCTS (HPN)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)</IN><NS>NEW PRODUCTS andamp; SERVICES (PDT)</NS><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   BETHEL, Conn. -- Battery maker Duracell Inc. said it plansto produce mercury-free alkaline batteries for shipment toretailers by mid-1992.   The company will offer the batteries in the standardconsumer sizes, from AA to 9-volt, at current prices. Asproduction increases it will phase out its other batteriesthrough inventory reduction.</LP><TEXT>   Small amounts of mercury are used in household batteriesto control the formation of gas. Battery makers have had toreformulate and redesign batteries to provide the sameperformance without using mercury.   A number of localities are moving to ban disposal ofbatteries containing mercury and are requiring manufacturersto make arrangements to collect used batteries. Severalbattery makers have announced new designs that virtuallyeliminate mercury in the design.</TEXT></DOC>